<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">Notes</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">
<taxonomicName class="Monocotyledoneae" family="Commelinaceae" genus="Commelina" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Commelina benghalensis" order="Commelinales" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="benghalensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">Commelina benghalensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a weed from the Old World subtropics. In the Canary Islands, it is only known from Gran Canaria (
<bibRefCitation author="Acebes Ginoves, J R" journalOrPublisher="Gobierno de Canarias, La Laguna" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" refId="B6456181" refString="Acebes Ginoves, J R, Leon Arencibia, M C, Rodriguez Navarro, M L, 2010. Lista de especies silvestres de Canarias. Hongos, plantas y animales terrestres. Gobierno de Canarias, La Laguna" title="Lista de especies silvestres de Canarias. Hongos, plantas y animales terrestres." year="2010">
Acebes 
<normalizedToken originalValue="GinovÃ©s">Ginoves</normalizedToken>
et al. 2010
</bibRefCitation>
), although most (if not all) records probably date back to the 19th century (e.g. 
<bibRefCitation author="Buch, CL" journalOrPublisher="Archives de Botanique" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" pagination="481 - 508" refId="B6508930" refString="Buch, CL, 1833. Catalogue des Plantes spontanees qui ont ete jusqu'ici trouvees dans les iles Canaries. Archives de Botanique 1: 481 - 508" title="Catalogue des Plantes spontanees qui ont ete jusqu'ici trouvees dans les iles Canaries" volume="1" year="1833">Buch 1833</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">Since 2015, it has been known from a single locality in Tenerife. In Palm-Mar, it persists on the wall of a manhole. Its presence was regularly confirmed since then.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">
This species differs from the common and invasive 
<taxonomicName class="Monocotyledoneae" family="Commelinaceae" genus="Commelina" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Commelina" order="Commelinales" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">Commelina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species in the Canary Islands (
<taxonomicName authority="" authorityName="" class="Centricae" family="Chironomidae" genus="C." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="C. diffusa" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" phylum="Diatomeae" rank="species" species="diffusa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">C. diffusa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) by the spathe margins that are fused near base. This characteristic is shared with 
<taxonomicName authority="" authorityName="" class="Centricae" family="Chironomidae" genus="C." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="C. latifolia" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" phylum="Diatomeae" rank="species" species="latifolia">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">C. latifolia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Hochst. ex A. Rich., an African species that recently naturalised in La Palma (
<bibRefCitation author="Otto, R" journalOrPublisher="Collectanea Botanica" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" refId="B6509388" refString="Otto, R, Verloove, F, 2016. New xenophytes from La Palma (Canary Islands, Spain), with emphasis on naturalized and (potentially) invasive species. Collectanea Botanica 35" title="New xenophytes from La Palma (Canary Islands, Spain), with emphasis on naturalized and (potentially) invasive species" volume="35" year="2016">Otto and Verloove 2016</bibRefCitation>
). It can be distinguished from the latter by the typical pubescence that consists of reddish hairs and all petals, including the minute lower one, being blue.
</paragraph>
